tr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/J003689/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This project investigates the mechanisms that govern the occupational choices of African workers, as well as the monetary and non-monetary returns to their decisions. Its main objective is to enhance our understanding of labour markets in Africa and to inform policymakers who are engaged in the design of employment policies, growth enhancing interventions for micro-entrepreneurs and social security for the developing world.&lt;br />&lt;br />The first part of the project investigates how African workers allocate themselves between different sectors of the economy. Through novel experimental data, the analysis explores the role of risk-aversion, which is found to be an important determinant of workers? distribution between formal and informal jobs.&lt;br />&lt;br />The second part focuses on the largest occupational category in the developing world, self-employed workers with small productive activities; and it estimates their returns to different productive assets, namely physical capital, labour and human capital, highlighting potential obstacles to growth.&lt;br />&lt;br />The third part returns to the issue of uncertainty, exploring the direct welfare implications of income insecurity for workers? wellbeing. Based on unique panel data on happiness, the analysis strongly suggests that earning security is a fundamental determinant of workers? welfare, lending direct support to the creation of earning safety nets in developing countries.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2014-03-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2012-03-31</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>156041</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativePr